Dear Hiring Team,

It is with great pleasure that I submit my candidacy for the *Full Stack Engineer* role with *Nash*. I bring over three years of professional experience building full-stack web applications, Python backend services, and real-time operator dashboards in production, along with a strong academic foundation as a Master of Science in Computer Science graduate from Pace University, NY.

Through my experience across two engineering roles, I have built and delivered production-grade full-stack systems that directly reflect the end-to-end ownership across React, TypeScript, and Python this position demands. At Sperse, I engineered a React and TypeScript visual workflow platform with component-driven architecture and WebSocket-driven Redis Pub/Sub feeds for real-time execution status across operator dashboards — the same kind of high-performance, operator-facing portal Nash is building for logistics. Alongside it, I built a full-stack Python FastAPI CRM platform serving 10,000+ users, exposing RESTful APIs backed by PostgreSQL to route requests across 40+ specialized sub-agents with tenant-aware access control, and designed a Python backend service exposing 160+ typed RESTful endpoints with Pydantic validation and OpenTelemetry instrumentation across microservice-oriented workflows. I also built CI/CD pipelines for full-stack deployments that gate every release with OpenTelemetry trace-based evals flagging latency, accuracy, and safety regressions before they reach customers. Prior to Sperse, at Qualitest I designed a cloud-agnostic Storage Service in Java and Spring Boot with PostgreSQL and Redis handling file operations across Google Cloud Storage, S3, and MinIO via signed URLs, optimized PostgreSQL with window functions and materialized views while exposing the results through interactive React visualizations, and orchestrated long-running jobs with AWS Step Functions across 100K+ weekly executions — giving me direct, hands-on experience with the cloud-native, production-scale full-stack systems that require both frontend polish and backend resilience.

My personal project, Dark Factory, sharpened my instincts for the hardest part of real-time operator interfaces: keeping the dashboard trustworthy under failure. I designed the TypeScript task-dispatch layer with WebSocket-driven progress feeds so operators could monitor live agent execution status and intervene on stalled or failed subtasks across the fleet — the same challenge Nash's portal faces when conditions on the ground shift and dispatchers need every delivery in motion visible in front of them. Building it demanded the same care for loading states, error recovery, and real-time data freshness that determines whether an operator trusts the product on a quiet Tuesday or a day when a storm closes half the routes.

I have always been passionate about closing the gap between consumer expectations and operational reality — the Logistics Singularity Nash is built to solve — and envision myself contributing my talent to the furthering of Nash's mission to unify decisioning, execution, and capacity into a single programmable system that runs the operation at equilibrium. I would love to discuss my interest in this position with your team and can be reached at #ph or #eml. Thank you for your time and consideration, I look forward to connecting!

